   <section1 id="sFocus">
	  <secTitle>Topic and Focus Constructions</secTitle>
	  <p contentType="ctPracticalIntro"><content>
		 This section considers two types of constructions which draw attention to a particular element.  Since topics occur outside of focus constructions and have greater scope, they will be considered first.  It is possible for a single sentence to have both a topic and a focused phrase.</content></p>
      <p contentType="ctComparativeIntro"><content>
         This section considers two types of constructions which draw attention to a particular element.  Since topics occur outside of focus constructions and have greater scope, they will be considered first.  The example </content><langData>As for Bill, soccer he plays __ best</langData><content> shows that a single sentence may have both a topic and a focused phrase.  In this case, the topic </content><langData>Bill</langData><content> is introduced by the topic marker </content><langData>as for</langData><content>, then the focused phrase </content><langData>soccer</langData><content>, which has been moved out of its regular place in the sentence follows.</content></p>
   <section2 id="sFocusTopics">
		 <secTitle>Topics and Topic Markers</secTitle>
		 <p contentType="ctPracticalIntro"><content>
			As defined here, topic constructions consist of a topic phrase followed by a complete sentence or question and usually set apart by punctuation.  Certain markers may be used to set off topics. </content>
 </p>
      <p contentType="ctComparativeIntro"><content>
         As defined here, topic constructions consist of a topic phrase followed by a complete sentence or question and usually set apart by punctuation.  Certain markers may be used to set off topics, as shown in the following English examples: </content>
         <langData>As for John, I think he will make a good doctor</langData><content> and </content><langData>Speaking of Jill, where is she?</langData>    </p>
      
		 <p show="swTopicNo"><langName/><content> does not allow topic phrases. </content></p>
		 <p show="swTopicYes"><langName/><content> has topic phrases which occur </content>
            <case element="focus" attr="topicPos">
			   <caseText value="before">before</caseText>
			   <caseText value="after">after</caseText>
			   <caseText value="unknown">_______</caseText>
            </case>
            <content> the main sentence or question.   Some examples include:</content>
		 </p>
		 <example show="swTopicYes">
			<interlinear exampleLoc="focus/topicExample"/>
		 </example>
		 <p show="swTopicYes"><content>As the examples show, the topic phrase in </content><langName/><content> is </content>
			<case element="focus" attr="topicMarker">
			   <caseText value="no">not marked by a topic marker.  Only the position in the sentence and possibly punctuation distinguish the topic phrase.</caseText>
			   <caseText value="yesWord">marked by certain words or phrases.</caseText>
			   <caseText value="yesClitic">marked by one or more clitics which attach to the topic phrase.  These clitics are: </caseText>
			   <caseText value="yesAffix">marked by one or more affixes which attach to the head noun in the topic phrase.  These affixes are: </caseText>
			</case>
			<text show="swTopicMarkerYesWord"><content>The topic markers occur </content>
			   <text show="swTopicMarkerBefore"><content>before</content></text>
			   <text show="swTopicMarkerAfter"><content>after</content></text>
			   <text show="swTopicMarkerBoth"><content>on both sides of</content></text>
			   <text show="swTopicMarkerEither"><content>on either side of</content></text>
			   <text show="swTopicMarkerBeforeOrBoth"><content>before or on both sides of</content></text>
			   <text show="swTopicMarkerAfterOrBoth"><content>after or on both sides of</content></text>
			   <text show="swTopicMarkerEitherOrBoth"><content>on either side or on both sides of</content></text>
			   <text show="swTopicMarkerNotOther"><content> the topic phrase.  </content>
			   </text>
			   <text show="swTopicMarkerOtherOnly"><content>___</content><contentCheckBoxOther contentLoc="focus/topicMarkerOther"/><content>.  </content>
			   </text>
			   <text show="swTopicMarkerAndOther"><content> the topic phrase and may also occur ___</content><contentCheckBoxOther contentLoc="focus/topicMarkerOther"/><content>.  </content></text>
			   <content> A topic marker is </content><case element="focus" attr="topicMarkerRequired">
				  <caseText value="no">optional</caseText>
				  <caseText value="yes">required</caseText></case>
			   <content> whenever there is a topic phrase.  The topic markers are:</content>
			</text>
		 </p>
